1
00:00:02,630 --> 00:00:06,111
I'm going to go ahead and get started.

2
00:00:06,111 --> 00:00:08,992
Everyone, welcome. Thank you for showing up today.

3
00:00:08,992 --> 00:00:12,173
Good morning, good afternoon, depending on your state

4
00:00:12,173 --> 00:00:14,054
of jet-laggedness. Is that a word?

5
00:00:14,054 --> 00:00:15,334
Can I use jet-laggedness?

6
00:00:15,334 --> 00:00:18,195
Please remember to turn off your cell phones

7
00:00:18,195 --> 00:00:20,576
and all that other fun stuff that we typically tell you

8
00:00:20,576 --> 00:00:23,877
before one of these talks. My name is Jim Brown.

9
00:00:23,877 --> 00:00:26,197
I am from Epic Games,

10
00:00:26,197 --> 00:00:30,179
and my talk today is rational to emotional designs

11
00:00:30,179 --> 00:00:31,319
that increase retention.

12
00:00:32,297 --> 00:00:36,938
And the word rational generally has very positive connotations,

13
00:00:36,938 --> 00:00:40,279
which might lead people to believe that if they're making rational decisions,

14
00:00:40,279 --> 00:00:42,060
they are therefore making good decisions.

15
00:00:42,060 --> 00:00:48,622
And that's not always the case, because we're actually very often influenced

16
00:00:48,622 --> 00:00:50,982
by powerful emotions first,

17
00:00:50,982 --> 00:00:54,563
that we then try to rationalize the why after the fact.

18
00:00:55,601 --> 00:00:59,303
And as I talk about emotions today, I want to be very clear that I'm not talking about

19
00:00:59,303 --> 00:01:02,045
ways to make players happy or sad.

20
00:01:02,045 --> 00:01:03,086
Those are feelings.

21
00:01:03,086 --> 00:01:08,790
Emotions are those core parts of us that are physical and instinctive.

22
00:01:08,790 --> 00:01:13,213
They're programmed into us after years and years of evolution.

23
00:01:14,225 --> 00:01:16,646
And that makes them more universal to us as humans,

24
00:01:16,646 --> 00:01:19,168
as opposed to the feelings which make it,

25
00:01:19,168 --> 00:01:22,710
which are more unique to us as individuals.

26
00:01:22,710 --> 00:01:24,732
And emotional design, therefore,

27
00:01:24,732 --> 00:01:28,694
gives us the capability to reach a broader audience

28
00:01:28,694 --> 00:01:29,915
in a deeper way.

29
00:01:29,915 --> 00:01:32,757
So I'll start today with a brief introduction

30
00:01:32,757 --> 00:01:33,898
to what emotional design is,

31
00:01:33,898 --> 00:01:35,059
because not a lot of people

32
00:01:35,059 --> 00:01:37,020
are really familiar with it, I believe.

33
00:01:37,020 --> 00:01:39,642
And then roll into some more concrete examples

34
00:01:39,642 --> 00:01:41,503
of how you can use it in your designs

35
00:01:41,503 --> 00:01:42,964
to help improve retention.

36
00:01:45,395 --> 00:01:50,999
While he likely doesn't need too much introduction with this audience, I hope, I do want to cover my bases.

37
00:01:50,999 --> 00:01:55,782
So this Dapper Fellow is of course Don Norman, a UX pioneer and icon.

38
00:01:55,782 --> 00:02:02,667
And he actually has a book about emotional design where he describes the specific design elements

39
00:02:02,667 --> 00:02:09,031
that help us form attachments to things and how those attachments can help or can influence

40
00:02:09,031 --> 00:02:10,933
our experience using them.

41
00:02:11,839 --> 00:02:16,207
He says that good emotional design has three major components.

42
00:02:16,207 --> 00:02:20,414
The visceral component, behavioral component, and a reflective component.

43
00:02:20,869 --> 00:02:22,891
Now, the visceral, of course, is your gut reactions

44
00:02:22,891 --> 00:02:24,752
or how you respond to a stimulus.

45
00:02:24,752 --> 00:02:29,455
The behavioral asks, is something actually useful?

46
00:02:29,455 --> 00:02:32,257
Does it perform the way it's supposed to?

47
00:02:32,257 --> 00:02:35,960
And can it, through its use, somehow influence or change

48
00:02:35,960 --> 00:02:36,641
your behavior?

49
00:02:36,641 --> 00:02:39,363
And then the reflectant component is,

50
00:02:39,363 --> 00:02:40,804
does it make me think about it?

51
00:02:40,804 --> 00:02:43,966
Especially after it's gone, do I think about it,

52
00:02:43,966 --> 00:02:46,248
the object that I was using, when it's no longer there?

53
00:02:46,248 --> 00:02:46,308
Now.

54
00:02:48,457 --> 00:02:55,501
Looking at each of these individually, that visceral component is really, really easy for us to get as a designer.

55
00:02:55,501 --> 00:02:59,723
But visceral reactions tend to be very unpredictable.

56
00:02:59,723 --> 00:03:01,824
And as an example, I give you this.

57
00:03:01,824 --> 00:03:09,068
I can almost guarantee that everyone here has some sort of visceral reaction to seeing this image.

58
00:03:09,068 --> 00:03:15,432
But the problem is, I can't tell whether you're going to respond positively or negatively.

59
00:03:16,358 --> 00:03:19,762
because those reactions tend to be very personal

60
00:03:19,762 --> 00:03:22,344
based on your own context and experience.

61
00:03:23,463 --> 00:03:25,263
Visceral reactions are also very transient.

62
00:03:25,263 --> 00:03:27,684
So even though I've left this up here

63
00:03:27,684 --> 00:03:29,325
while I've continued to talk,

64
00:03:29,325 --> 00:03:30,725
it's probably even in that short time,

65
00:03:30,725 --> 00:03:33,306
any emotional response that you had

66
00:03:33,306 --> 00:03:35,887
has probably started to fade away.

67
00:03:35,887 --> 00:03:37,868
So as a designer, you need to be very careful

68
00:03:37,868 --> 00:03:40,829
with your use of visceral design.

69
00:03:40,829 --> 00:03:42,829
Monster closets stop being fun,

70
00:03:42,829 --> 00:03:47,851
large explosions stop having the impact that they had,

71
00:03:47,851 --> 00:03:49,932
and the transient.

72
00:03:50,332 --> 00:03:54,514
unpredictable nature of these visceral reactions means that alone they aren't

73
00:03:54,514 --> 00:04:01,477
very good for retention except that they are incredibly important for making

74
00:04:01,477 --> 00:04:07,080
first impressions. So visceral designs can be a crutch that you can use to get

75
00:04:07,080 --> 00:04:12,122
people interested early or to obtain very short-term retention goals like hey

76
00:04:12,122 --> 00:04:17,225
come back the next day while you rely on other methods for longer-term retention.

77
00:04:19,661 --> 00:04:26,745
By contrast, game systems are specifically designed to affect the player over long periods.

78
00:04:26,745 --> 00:04:32,429
As time goes on, the systems can affect player emotion, and that can in turn affect their

79
00:04:32,429 --> 00:04:32,969
behavior.

80
00:04:33,923 --> 00:04:36,026
And the really cool thing about game systems

81
00:04:36,026 --> 00:04:38,029
is that they can then respond to those changes,

82
00:04:38,029 --> 00:04:42,055
which resets or continues the cycle.

83
00:04:42,055 --> 00:04:43,637
And this sets up a feedback loop,

84
00:04:43,637 --> 00:04:46,501
so the game system actually has the ability

85
00:04:46,501 --> 00:04:51,248
to respond to both behavioral and emotional state changes.

86
00:04:53,069 --> 00:04:59,491
As an example, spree systems tend to have very good emotional design.

87
00:04:59,491 --> 00:05:03,973
In many games, including Epic's own Paragon and Unreal Tournament that I have up here,

88
00:05:03,973 --> 00:05:09,315
an announcer will come on and say things like, oh, killing spree or your power grows.

89
00:05:09,315 --> 00:05:14,797
These messages are feedback that communicate how well you're doing in a match, but they

90
00:05:14,797 --> 00:05:16,918
also serve a much larger purpose.

91
00:05:17,528 --> 00:05:20,069
When you're on a spree, your heart rate rises,

92
00:05:20,069 --> 00:05:21,650
that adrenaline starts to pump,

93
00:05:21,650 --> 00:05:24,851
and this is your visceral emotional reaction.

94
00:05:24,851 --> 00:05:26,651
And since you're doing well,

95
00:05:26,651 --> 00:05:29,372
you might push the attack on an enemy

96
00:05:29,372 --> 00:05:32,553
that you would not have otherwise,

97
00:05:32,553 --> 00:05:33,954
and that is a behavioral reaction.

98
00:05:33,954 --> 00:05:36,615
In fact, by broadcasting your spree

99
00:05:36,615 --> 00:05:38,275
to everyone in the match,

100
00:05:38,275 --> 00:05:41,516
this system can also affect teammates,

101
00:05:41,516 --> 00:05:43,177
maybe by inspiring them,

102
00:05:43,177 --> 00:05:45,478
or enemies by intimidating them.

103
00:05:46,479 --> 00:05:49,642
meaning that your killing spree has the potential

104
00:05:49,642 --> 00:05:52,706
to affect everyone's behavior in the entire match.

105
00:05:52,706 --> 00:05:56,131
The system can then respond to that spree

106
00:05:56,131 --> 00:05:57,713
by making you a more high-value target

107
00:05:57,713 --> 00:05:59,455
or various other systems that people use,

108
00:05:59,455 --> 00:06:03,900
which encourages further behavioral and emotional change.

109
00:06:04,926 --> 00:06:14,009
And the design of these systems is so effective that this UltraKill t-shirt has become one of the top selling items in our online store

110
00:06:14,009 --> 00:06:21,952
showing that the Spree system is also very reflective, playing into the last of Norman's components for good emotional design

111
00:06:21,952 --> 00:06:27,333
And while these components are all interesting individually

112
00:06:28,629 --> 00:06:32,271
It really gets interesting when they start to come together

113
00:06:32,271 --> 00:06:34,792
all at the same time in one single design.

114
00:06:34,792 --> 00:06:39,574
And that's what Norman calls providing a emotional context.

115
00:06:39,574 --> 00:06:42,816
If you think about your typical game interaction,

116
00:06:42,816 --> 00:06:45,597
that you start with this kind of physical influence

117
00:06:45,597 --> 00:06:47,998
that's imposed by the input device,

118
00:06:47,998 --> 00:06:50,239
mouse, keyboard, VR helmet, touchscreen,

119
00:06:50,239 --> 00:06:51,279
whatever it is that you're using.

120
00:06:51,279 --> 00:06:54,541
And that determines the boundaries of what you can do.

121
00:06:55,505 --> 00:06:58,387
But then that logical or rational side of our brain kicks in

122
00:06:58,387 --> 00:07:02,752
and tries to figure out what we should be doing

123
00:07:02,752 --> 00:07:04,133
in the face of those physical limitations.

124
00:07:04,133 --> 00:07:08,197
But at an even higher level, what we can do, the physical,

125
00:07:08,197 --> 00:07:11,300
and even what we should do, the rational,

126
00:07:11,300 --> 00:07:14,923
often plays second fiddle to what we want to be doing,

127
00:07:14,923 --> 00:07:17,005
even if we can't explain why.

128
00:07:20,064 --> 00:07:25,108
And this is why I think emotional design is so important.

129
00:07:25,108 --> 00:07:28,991
By designing for emotion, we can reach that part of us

130
00:07:28,991 --> 00:07:32,653
that is universal to us as human beings

131
00:07:32,653 --> 00:07:34,515
and create a lasting impression

132
00:07:34,515 --> 00:07:38,578
that people want to come back for over and over again.

133
00:07:38,578 --> 00:07:41,660
But what does emotional design look like in actual practice

134
00:07:41,660 --> 00:07:44,402
and how does that lead to retention?

135
00:07:48,046 --> 00:07:49,667
Retention can actually manifest itself

136
00:07:49,667 --> 00:07:51,148
in a myriad of different ways,

137
00:07:51,148 --> 00:07:54,450
whether it's number of matches played,

138
00:07:54,450 --> 00:07:57,411
hours played, or days played in a row.

139
00:07:57,411 --> 00:07:59,452
It could be, is the user spending money

140
00:07:59,452 --> 00:08:01,593
or engaging with the game systems,

141
00:08:01,593 --> 00:08:03,755
combinations amongst all of those things.

142
00:08:04,304 --> 00:08:09,287
The one thing that they really have in common is that sense of attachment.

143
00:08:09,287 --> 00:08:12,469
And if you can recall, the purpose of emotional design

144
00:08:12,469 --> 00:08:19,352
is to give the user an emotional context that causes them to form attachments.

145
00:08:19,352 --> 00:08:23,074
So I want to go over some of the factors that might influence attachment today

146
00:08:23,074 --> 00:08:26,817
and discuss them alongside some examples from the games that I've worked on.

147
00:08:28,023 --> 00:08:32,126
And the categories I want to talk about in general are memory,

148
00:08:32,126 --> 00:08:35,608
patterns, feedback, and mental models.

149
00:08:35,608 --> 00:08:41,213
First on that list, of course, is memory.

150
00:08:41,213 --> 00:08:44,535
If we can design systems or games

151
00:08:44,535 --> 00:08:46,517
that stay in someone's memory,

152
00:08:46,517 --> 00:08:49,559
they're more likely to be reflective

153
00:08:49,559 --> 00:08:53,121
and therefore more likely to retain in the longer term.

154
00:08:54,135 --> 00:08:56,818
but the brain isn't a computer that stores

155
00:08:56,818 --> 00:08:59,662
and retrieves information.

156
00:08:59,662 --> 00:09:03,267
So memories can't just be programmed into them.

157
00:09:03,267 --> 00:09:05,029
We sometimes talk about brains that way.

158
00:09:06,346 --> 00:09:10,948
I even do it a lot in this presentation, but that's more just a shorthand that we use.

159
00:09:10,948 --> 00:09:16,650
The reality is that the brain is actually more akin to a system that is affected by

160
00:09:16,650 --> 00:09:19,811
and responds to stimuli.

161
00:09:19,811 --> 00:09:27,014
And we are constantly awash in an avalanche of feedback and input from our surroundings,

162
00:09:27,014 --> 00:09:27,534
from everywhere.

163
00:09:27,534 --> 00:09:32,657
So the way that we compensate for this is that we filter.

164
00:09:33,768 --> 00:09:36,648
And memory is therefore tied to attention.

165
00:09:36,648 --> 00:09:39,569
Where we choose to focus our attention

166
00:09:39,569 --> 00:09:43,090
affects what we will remember.

167
00:09:43,090 --> 00:09:48,931
But attention is, of course, a very limited resource.

168
00:09:48,931 --> 00:09:51,751
And when you're focused on playing a game,

169
00:09:51,751 --> 00:09:53,532
your brain is locked in this battle

170
00:09:53,532 --> 00:09:56,072
to prioritize what's happening in the moment,

171
00:09:56,072 --> 00:09:57,572
what's happening in the story,

172
00:09:57,572 --> 00:09:58,772
what are your short-term goals,

173
00:09:58,772 --> 00:10:00,253
what are your long-term goals.

174
00:10:00,801 --> 00:10:07,729
And so the peak-end rule is a very good way to help you determine when is a good time

175
00:10:07,729 --> 00:10:12,735
to try and focus the player's attention so that it has the most lasting potential.

176
00:10:13,947 --> 00:10:15,708
When we look at something that's happened to us,

177
00:10:15,708 --> 00:10:20,892
our brains kind of look at how we felt at the peak

178
00:10:20,892 --> 00:10:23,714
and the end of that experience.

179
00:10:23,714 --> 00:10:27,817
And over time, those two points are much more likely

180
00:10:27,817 --> 00:10:29,578
to be the brain's reference

181
00:10:29,578 --> 00:10:32,741
for our overall emotional experience.

182
00:10:32,741 --> 00:10:35,723
So if you can focus on making the peak and the end

183
00:10:35,723 --> 00:10:38,945
the most vivid, the most meaningful to the player,

184
00:10:38,945 --> 00:10:41,367
then they become the most available

185
00:10:41,367 --> 00:10:43,268
and lasting to long-term memory.

186
00:10:43,980 --> 00:10:48,965
And this is one of the reasons that people can suffer through extremely difficult encounters,

187
00:10:48,965 --> 00:10:52,348
or long levels, or difficult quest chains,

188
00:10:52,348 --> 00:10:55,731
and still come away from that experience feeling very good.

189
00:10:55,731 --> 00:10:59,734
Quick example from Gears of War.

190
00:10:59,734 --> 00:11:06,160
The sequence shown in this shot was, for many of our players, the peak experience of the game.

191
00:11:06,908 --> 00:11:11,712
There's this cool dramatic intro that led to an extremely difficult combat sequence

192
00:11:11,712 --> 00:11:15,555
where we introduced a key new enemy for the first time.

193
00:11:15,555 --> 00:11:18,698
And the line at the end of that intro, which you can see up here,

194
00:11:18,698 --> 00:11:22,361
look at all that juice, was funny, it was memorable,

195
00:11:22,361 --> 00:11:24,582
and it actually did become a meme

196
00:11:24,582 --> 00:11:27,565
that we saw resonating through the internet for a while.

197
00:11:27,565 --> 00:11:31,428
It showed up in other games and forms of achievements and all this other craziness.

198
00:11:31,428 --> 00:11:34,850
And during development, we knew that this was going to be a key moment in the game.

199
00:11:35,444 --> 00:11:37,346
And we didn't want players to miss that funny,

200
00:11:37,346 --> 00:11:38,867
we didn't want them to miss the drama,

201
00:11:38,867 --> 00:11:40,929
and we definitely didn't want them to miss

202
00:11:40,929 --> 00:11:42,550
the introduction to this new enemy

203
00:11:42,550 --> 00:11:44,872
because it was a key part of the game.

204
00:11:44,872 --> 00:11:46,594
So we decided to put a checkpoint right here.

205
00:11:46,594 --> 00:11:50,397
But that was a very rational decision.

206
00:11:50,397 --> 00:11:53,179
On paper, it sounded smart, it sounded reasonable.

207
00:11:53,179 --> 00:11:55,521
In the end, this actually turned out

208
00:11:55,521 --> 00:11:59,485
to be one of the biggest drop points in the entire game.

209
00:12:00,516 --> 00:12:07,319
Even years later, there is a thread on NeoGAF that discusses games with the worst checkpoints

210
00:12:07,319 --> 00:12:08,980
of all time.

211
00:12:08,980 --> 00:12:12,021
And you can guess what that thread is called.

212
00:12:12,021 --> 00:12:13,201
Look at all that juice.

213
00:12:13,201 --> 00:12:19,224
This sequence had a very strong rational design, but poor emotional design.

214
00:12:19,942 --> 00:12:24,467
It showed no empathy for players stuck in a very difficult part of the game,

215
00:12:24,467 --> 00:12:28,151
and no respect for their time as they had to repeat this over and over

216
00:12:28,151 --> 00:12:31,294
and walk through this long sequence and watch that same cinematic

217
00:12:31,294 --> 00:12:34,938
and go through that same fight every single time they died.

218
00:12:34,938 --> 00:12:39,963
And my favorite post in that thread says,

219
00:12:39,963 --> 00:12:43,586
it's amazing that game designers still don't get things like that.

220
00:12:43,973 --> 00:12:48,836
And they're right, because it's so easy for us to rationalize a poor decision

221
00:12:48,836 --> 00:12:51,658
and forget the power of emotional design.

222
00:12:51,658 --> 00:12:57,461
Compare that to a more recent example that we're working on in our game Fortnite.

223
00:12:58,478 --> 00:13:03,780
Instead of generic loot crates, Fortnite uses llama pinatas.

224
00:13:03,780 --> 00:13:05,040
And as one does with a pinata,

225
00:13:05,040 --> 00:13:07,840
the way you open it is to beat it with a stick.

226
00:13:07,840 --> 00:13:12,021
So there's this really strong affordance for hitting it,

227
00:13:12,021 --> 00:13:14,702
which is a very strong visceral reaction.

228
00:13:14,702 --> 00:13:17,582
And when you pull back and you're about to unleash

229
00:13:17,582 --> 00:13:21,143
your attack, at the peak of this experience,

230
00:13:21,143 --> 00:13:24,504
the llama reacts, inciting a behavioral response from you,

231
00:13:24,504 --> 00:13:26,024
because now you want to hit it even harder.

232
00:13:26,963 --> 00:13:30,266
Or maybe you feel sorry for it, whatever your deal is there.

233
00:13:30,266 --> 00:13:34,829
The pinata theme, the actions, and of course,

234
00:13:34,829 --> 00:13:37,551
the end result, getting all the loot,

235
00:13:37,551 --> 00:13:40,413
help players remember that it's more than just a loot crate,

236
00:13:40,413 --> 00:13:43,055
making an experience that players reflect on.

237
00:13:43,055 --> 00:13:45,237
But opening this thing is a really long sequence,

238
00:13:45,237 --> 00:13:48,940
and you have to use this broom to clean up

239
00:13:48,940 --> 00:13:50,441
all the pieces at the end.

240
00:13:51,878 --> 00:13:54,720
and you do it pretty regularly every time you earn something,

241
00:13:54,720 --> 00:13:57,281
but then up in the top right, there's also a fast-forward button

242
00:13:57,281 --> 00:14:00,243
that shows empathy and respect for the player's time.

243
00:14:00,243 --> 00:14:05,485
Now, each of these sequences from the two games are memorable,

244
00:14:05,485 --> 00:14:06,746
but for opposite reasons,

245
00:14:06,746 --> 00:14:09,227
both insight and emotional response from the player,

246
00:14:09,227 --> 00:14:14,210
but Gears does it in a way that pushes the player out of the game experience,

247
00:14:14,210 --> 00:14:18,032
and it takes their attention away from what they're actually trying to do.

248
00:14:18,995 --> 00:14:21,517
while Fortnite grabs the player's attention

249
00:14:21,517 --> 00:14:25,060
