flat cannons 2-4, rocket launcher was 3-4,

501
00:28:32,538 --> 00:28:35,879
I mean these patterned through all of our weapons.

502
00:28:35,879 --> 00:28:38,301
This made them easier to use

503
00:28:38,301 --> 00:28:42,103
because the recognizable patterns allowed players

504
00:28:42,103 --> 00:28:44,864
to predict the firing state of an enemy,

505
00:28:44,864 --> 00:28:47,585
to understand the length of their reloads,

506
00:28:47,585 --> 00:28:50,147
and time the button presses on their shots.

507
00:28:50,147 --> 00:28:53,508
And best of all, this requires no effort

508
00:28:53,508 --> 00:28:54,789
on the part of the player.

509
00:28:55,282 --> 00:28:58,545
because it's affecting them at an unconscious, emotional level.

510
00:28:58,545 --> 00:29:02,129
These patterns exist purely to help the player,

511
00:29:02,129 --> 00:29:04,952
but from their perspective, they're not being helped,

512
00:29:04,952 --> 00:29:06,254
they're just playing the game better.

513
00:29:06,254 --> 00:29:08,616
And since they feel more successful,

514
00:29:08,616 --> 00:29:11,159
they experience growth and progression,

515
00:29:11,159 --> 00:29:14,203
which means they're more likely to come back and try for more.

516
00:29:16,712 --> 00:29:19,854
Social patterns are very important to retention.

517
00:29:19,854 --> 00:29:21,555
This could be an entire talk of its own.

518
00:29:21,555 --> 00:29:23,616
I don't have time to go into everything today,

519
00:29:23,616 --> 00:29:26,398
but just as a brief summary, I wanted to go over them

520
00:29:26,398 --> 00:29:30,060
because they can be so incredibly compelling.

521
00:29:30,060 --> 00:29:32,822
Whether people are in a guild or a clan

522
00:29:32,822 --> 00:29:35,864
or whatever your game's social group is,

523
00:29:35,864 --> 00:29:38,525
or even if they're just playing as part of a team.

524
00:29:39,330 --> 00:29:43,152
that social structure itself leads to increased engagement.

525
00:29:43,152 --> 00:29:45,493
Congregate is a mobile publisher,

526
00:29:45,493 --> 00:29:51,136
they released this data a while back that shows that more than half of

527
00:29:51,136 --> 00:29:54,698
their revenue comes from 0.5 percent of

528
00:29:54,698 --> 00:29:58,080
the population that has played their game for more than 500 hours.

529
00:29:58,080 --> 00:30:02,382
Every single one of their top 10 games has a guild,

530
00:30:02,382 --> 00:30:06,244
and guild players spend 10 times more than non-guild players.

531
00:30:06,953 --> 00:30:09,073
Among the people who do spend money,

532
00:30:09,073 --> 00:30:12,994
guild players spend three times more than people who aren't in a guild.

533
00:30:12,994 --> 00:30:15,634
Most relevant to today's talk,

534
00:30:15,634 --> 00:30:19,555
social ties led to an increase in engagement.

535
00:30:19,555 --> 00:30:23,416
Players in social groups spend more money,

536
00:30:23,416 --> 00:30:26,356
they play longer, and they play deeper.

537
00:30:26,356 --> 00:30:28,536
They retain much, much better.

538
00:30:28,536 --> 00:30:32,897
We saw the same effect when we introduced co-op to Gears of War

539
00:30:32,897 --> 00:30:34,958
and our Unreal series,

540
00:30:34,958 --> 00:30:36,378
especially when we hit...

541
00:30:37,363 --> 00:30:42,425
horde mode, led to huge gains in player retention for us

542
00:30:42,425 --> 00:30:46,106
because we created a social pattern.

543
00:30:46,106 --> 00:30:47,926
Co-op game types encourage repeat play

544
00:30:47,926 --> 00:30:50,027
because every time you go to play,

545
00:30:50,027 --> 00:30:51,407
you're with a different group

546
00:30:51,407 --> 00:30:53,888
and you're gonna have a different experience.

547
00:30:53,888 --> 00:30:57,069
And if you didn't do so well this time,

548
00:30:57,069 --> 00:30:58,170
try again with a different group.

549
00:30:59,289 --> 00:31:03,093
Cooperation is also more motivating and rewarding

550
00:31:03,093 --> 00:31:06,317
than competition because the social connections

551
00:31:06,317 --> 00:31:09,100
create a sense of belonging and a sense of duty.

552
00:31:09,100 --> 00:31:11,723
They give you a reason to stick around and keep playing

553
00:31:11,723 --> 00:31:14,427
because you don't want to leave and hurt your team.

554
00:31:17,595 --> 00:31:21,176
Another really important social pattern in games is gifting.

555
00:31:21,176 --> 00:31:25,397
Gifts help us establish positive emotional responses

556
00:31:25,397 --> 00:31:29,218
from players and, thanks to our lovely human nature,

557
00:31:29,218 --> 00:31:30,779
feelings of reciprocity.

558
00:31:30,779 --> 00:31:35,941
A gift serves as a reminder of the person who gave it to you.

559
00:31:35,941 --> 00:31:37,981
It starts setting up a relationship

560
00:31:37,981 --> 00:31:42,743
with that other person, and it encourages you to respond.

561
00:31:42,743 --> 00:31:46,584
This reciprocal pattern of behavior leads to engagement.

562
00:31:47,393 --> 00:31:49,915
in our new mobile game, which was just announced this morning,

563
00:31:49,915 --> 00:31:50,917
Battle Breakers.

564
00:31:50,917 --> 00:31:51,357
Go play it.

565
00:31:51,357 --> 00:31:54,600
The more engaged you are, the more you participate

566
00:31:54,600 --> 00:31:57,203
in daily activities, the better your gifts

567
00:31:57,203 --> 00:31:58,765
are for your friends.

568
00:31:58,765 --> 00:32:01,548
And this fosters a sense of social engagement

569
00:32:01,548 --> 00:32:04,611
and rewards players and their friends

570
00:32:04,611 --> 00:32:06,493
for the investment of their time, which

571
00:32:06,493 --> 00:32:10,637
encourages them to come back and return that favor again for you.

572
00:32:13,887 --> 00:32:18,628
You can also create social patterns by adding friends lists to your game.

573
00:32:18,628 --> 00:32:23,250
I mean, have you ever been compelled to accept a friend request from someone who you've never actually met?

574
00:32:23,250 --> 00:32:29,712
And when you send a friend's request, isn't there an automatic expectation that whoever you send it to is going to reply?

575
00:32:29,712 --> 00:32:36,375
Social networking is all about that expectation that there is a pattern there and that it will continue.

576
00:32:37,335 --> 00:32:40,798
So we carry on every day trying to build relationships

577
00:32:40,798 --> 00:32:46,042
and collect friends and likes and followers on social media.

578
00:32:46,042 --> 00:32:51,747
And we report our status with people who in reality,

579
00:32:51,747 --> 00:32:52,908
we have no actual relationship with.

580
00:32:52,908 --> 00:32:55,790
But we tend to think that we do.

581
00:32:55,790 --> 00:32:58,613
And that ever important emotional context

582
00:32:58,613 --> 00:33:01,155
motivates us to continue to come back

583
00:33:01,155 --> 00:33:03,176
again and again and again.

584
00:33:04,147 --> 00:33:06,328
And the key takeaway I want people to get here

585
00:33:06,328 --> 00:33:07,930
is that when you're designing patterns,

586
00:33:07,930 --> 00:33:11,332
consider not only how they affect player behavior,

587
00:33:11,332 --> 00:33:15,456
but also how they could impact player relationships.

588
00:33:15,456 --> 00:33:19,038
Because relationships provide a much larger

589
00:33:19,038 --> 00:33:23,082
emotional context that can dramatically improve retention.

590
00:33:24,835 --> 00:33:28,417
One final, one word of caution before moving on from patterns.

591
00:33:28,417 --> 00:33:31,079
Once a pattern is established, you

592
00:33:31,079 --> 00:33:34,361
have to be very careful about breaking it or interrupting it.

593
00:33:34,361 --> 00:33:37,663
There were times in Gears where we wanted to create a very

594
00:33:37,663 --> 00:33:40,064
impactful moment, like this scene here,

595
00:33:40,064 --> 00:33:43,486
where Dom visits the grave of his wife,

596
00:33:43,486 --> 00:33:46,547
who he had to euthanize after she had

597
00:33:46,547 --> 00:33:49,569
been tortured and lobotomized.

598
00:33:49,569 --> 00:33:50,430
Gears is a fun place.

599
00:33:52,105 --> 00:33:54,347
We really wanted this scene to have weight,

600
00:33:54,347 --> 00:33:55,808
to build up those feels in the player,

601
00:33:55,808 --> 00:33:59,450
and watching this sequence develop in our daily stand-ups,

602
00:33:59,450 --> 00:34:01,851
we were really happy with the way it was coming together.

603
00:34:01,851 --> 00:34:04,033
We finally get it in game, and there's Dom,

604
00:34:04,033 --> 00:34:07,695
kneeling next to the grave, saying his final goodbye.

605
00:34:07,695 --> 00:34:10,436
And then he stands up right afterwards,

606
00:34:10,436 --> 00:34:12,277
runs into combat, and starts yelling,

607
00:34:12,277 --> 00:34:15,459
this is gonna be awesome, oh yeah!

608
00:34:15,459 --> 00:34:15,519
Now.

609
00:34:17,645 --> 00:34:20,787
These were his dynamically generated combat scenes,

610
00:34:20,787 --> 00:34:25,011
which were playing as designed by our combat system,

611
00:34:25,011 --> 00:34:28,754
but contextually were really, really wrong.

612
00:34:28,754 --> 00:34:33,477
And the inclusion of this emotional scene

613
00:34:33,477 --> 00:34:36,260
broke that established pattern of combat.

614
00:34:36,260 --> 00:34:41,184
And it was so obvious that it made this scene with Dom

615
00:34:41,184 --> 00:34:43,305
comical instead of impactful.

616
00:34:43,305 --> 00:34:46,148
It was really bad emotional design.

617
00:34:47,408 --> 00:34:50,412
So of course we ended up modifying the system before we shipped

618
00:34:50,412 --> 00:34:52,354
so that we had a series of switches

619
00:34:52,354 --> 00:34:54,456
that would filter out specific lines

620
00:34:54,456 --> 00:34:58,902
in areas where we wanted to maintain an emotional momentum

621
00:34:58,902 --> 00:35:03,007
and to do it in a way that was so seamless to the player

622
00:35:03,007 --> 00:35:07,292
that it didn't interrupt that pattern of their emotional context.

623
00:35:09,707 --> 00:35:12,170
Patterns have a significant impact

624
00:35:12,170 --> 00:35:14,632
on the player's perception of your game.

625
00:35:14,632 --> 00:35:19,096
They determine that sense of pacing and flow.

626
00:35:19,096 --> 00:35:21,399
Repetition helps us build memories,

627
00:35:21,399 --> 00:35:25,563
and the consistency of action, feedback,

628
00:35:25,563 --> 00:35:29,186
and reward and expectation help players set goals

629
00:35:29,186 --> 00:35:31,008
and find meaning in your game,

630
00:35:31,008 --> 00:35:33,330
which can dramatically improve retention.

631
00:35:38,347 --> 00:35:40,308
All right, signs and feedback.

632
00:35:40,308 --> 00:35:44,590
Good feedback is obviously essential to UX,

633
00:35:44,590 --> 00:35:46,031
especially in game design.

634
00:35:46,031 --> 00:35:48,692
This is one of the biggest

635
00:35:48,692 --> 00:35:50,833
do not miss opportunities for any designer.

636
00:35:50,833 --> 00:35:55,456
Feedback is vital for clarity, communication,

637
00:35:55,456 --> 00:35:57,237
and successful pattern recognition.

638
00:35:57,237 --> 00:35:59,898
The player has to know what state they're in

639
00:35:59,898 --> 00:36:02,219
if you expect them to respond.

640
00:36:02,219 --> 00:36:03,100
Can they attack?

641
00:36:03,100 --> 00:36:04,920
Should they move?

642
00:36:04,920 --> 00:36:05,761
How should they react?

643
00:36:07,190 --> 00:36:12,011
Now we experience emotion as a direct and immediate result

644
00:36:12,011 --> 00:36:13,931
of our interaction with the world.

645
00:36:13,931 --> 00:36:18,372
So feedback needs to be just as immediate and crystal clear.

646
00:36:18,372 --> 00:36:21,753
We took this to the extreme in Gears.

647
00:36:21,753 --> 00:36:24,714
We focused on explosions with deep audio,

648
00:36:24,714 --> 00:36:27,775
visual effects that really kind of shook you to your core.

649
00:36:27,775 --> 00:36:30,795
We spent weeks working on just how much the screen

650
00:36:30,795 --> 00:36:31,916
would shake while you were running

651
00:36:31,916 --> 00:36:34,196
and the feedback that you would get

652
00:36:34,196 --> 00:36:35,437
when you were locked in a chainsaw duel.

653
00:36:36,383 --> 00:36:41,906
In Gears, you don't just get into cover, you slam into cover, and dust crumbles off the wall,

654
00:36:41,906 --> 00:36:47,468
and you hear the character grimace, and you can see the expression on their face.

655
00:36:47,468 --> 00:36:54,070
And that feedback helps the player feel the game experience in a very visceral way.

656
00:36:54,070 --> 00:36:57,571
In Paragon, we do very much the same thing.

657
00:36:58,402 --> 00:37:01,464
Whether it's launching a meteor or the impact against a shield,

658
00:37:01,464 --> 00:37:05,487
we do our best to ensure that this conflict is felt,

659
00:37:05,487 --> 00:37:07,208
not just seen or heard.

660
00:37:07,208 --> 00:37:11,150
In a lot of our marketing, like this image here,

661
00:37:11,150 --> 00:37:14,372
Gideon pulls a meteor out of a dimensional rift

662
00:37:14,372 --> 00:37:17,474
and slams it down into the enemy.

663
00:37:17,474 --> 00:37:20,296
But in the actual game, he actually

664
00:37:20,296 --> 00:37:24,119
launches a series of small meteors consecutively

665
00:37:24,119 --> 00:37:25,640
instead of just the one big one.

666
00:37:26,847 --> 00:37:29,710
And we tried to rationalize that decision by telling our players

667
00:37:29,710 --> 00:37:34,874
that the small meteors actually did more damage over a larger area,

668
00:37:34,874 --> 00:37:37,936
so it was actually a more effective way to attack.

669
00:37:37,936 --> 00:37:41,439
But from that visceral, emotional point of view,

670
00:37:41,439 --> 00:37:43,961
our players were still very disappointed.

671
00:37:43,961 --> 00:37:49,025
So we switched it to be a meteor, one big meteor, just like in that image.

672
00:37:49,932 --> 00:37:52,414
And sure enough, right when we did that,

673
00:37:52,414 --> 00:37:54,916
the use of Gideon in Paragon spiked.

674
00:37:54,916 --> 00:37:59,340
He almost instantly became one of the most popular heroes

675
00:37:59,340 --> 00:37:59,840
in the game.

676
00:37:59,840 --> 00:38:03,664
It's also important to note that at the same time

677
00:38:03,664 --> 00:38:06,606
we did this, we actually nerfed his abilities.

678
00:38:06,606 --> 00:38:09,749
So if you look at his win rate over that same period,

679
00:38:09,749 --> 00:38:13,672
it actually stays pretty consistent.

680
00:38:13,672 --> 00:38:17,715
He didn't actually get any better by any metric.

681
00:38:19,071 --> 00:38:23,515
But we improved retention by changing the game's effects

682
00:38:23,515 --> 00:38:28,399
in a way that provided better emotional feedback

683
00:38:28,399 --> 00:38:28,739
for our players.

684
00:38:28,739 --> 00:38:31,682
Feedback doesn't always need to be physical

685
00:38:31,682 --> 00:38:36,946
or even really obvious in order to be effective.

686
00:38:36,946 --> 00:38:39,809
Paragon uses these absolutely insane shaders

687
00:38:39,809 --> 00:38:40,950
for skin and hair.

688
00:38:40,950 --> 00:38:45,533
We have eyes that can actually dilate in response to light.

689
00:38:45,533 --> 00:38:47,295
It's completely over the top.

690
00:38:48,265 --> 00:38:52,587
but it makes our characters feel that much more human.

691
00:38:52,587 --> 00:38:56,589
And as humans, we're hardwired to react to another human

692
00:38:56,589 --> 00:38:59,730
differently than we would to a game character.

693
00:38:59,730 --> 00:39:04,472
And if the player's brain reacts to this character

694
00:39:04,472 --> 00:39:06,533
as it would to another human,

695
00:39:06,533 --> 00:39:09,014
instead of reacting to it like it would

696
00:39:09,014 --> 00:39:11,135
a collection of painted polygons,

697
00:39:11,135 --> 00:39:12,656
there's a much higher chance

698
00:39:12,656 --> 00:39:14,997
that they'll form that emotional connection.

699
00:39:15,903 --> 00:39:19,865
And while your standard visceral reactions to game characters

700
00:39:19,865 --> 00:39:24,408
tend to be very transient, these types of influences

701
00:39:24,408 --> 00:39:27,749
tend to stick around because we're cementing them

702
00:39:27,749 --> 00:39:29,470
at that emotional level.

703
00:39:29,470 --> 00:39:34,013
Now, of course, you don't need over-the-top visual effects

704
00:39:34,013 --> 00:39:35,394
to achieve those same goals.

705
00:39:35,394 --> 00:39:38,575
Sometimes even just a simple color shift

706
00:39:38,575 --> 00:39:40,356
can affect someone's retention.

707
00:39:41,218 --> 00:39:46,180
As I demonstrated earlier, Gears had a very, very dark storyline.

708
00:39:46,180 --> 00:39:49,701
And it got darker with every single iteration of the game.

709
00:39:49,701 --> 00:39:53,163
The first game was about the loss of home and family.

710
00:39:53,163 --> 00:39:57,824
The second game transitioned from small battles to these huge wars.

711
00:39:57,824 --> 00:40:01,686
And instead of losing friends, we were losing entire populations and cities.

712
00:40:01,686 --> 00:40:05,667
By the third game, we're dealing with the extinction of the human race

713
00:40:05,667 --> 00:40:07,968
and the potential destruction of the entire planet.

714
00:40:08,965 --> 00:40:12,407
Every game was more depressing than the last.

715
00:40:12,407 --> 00:40:15,509
And we really feared that this oppressive tone

716
00:40:15,509 --> 00:40:19,171
might overwhelm or turn away a lot of our players.

717
00:40:19,171 --> 00:40:23,233
So to counter that, we very intentionally tried to contrast

718
00:40:23,233 --> 00:40:26,615
the visual and emotional feedback channels.

719
00:40:26,615 --> 00:40:31,258
When the story became darker, the visuals became brighter,

720
00:40:31,258 --> 00:40:33,179
more colorful, and more saturated.

721
00:40:34,244 --> 00:40:37,025
This was less emotionally oppressive to people,

722
00:40:37,025 --> 00:40:38,265
so they stuck around longer.

723
00:40:38,265 --> 00:40:40,166
And while there are obviously

724
00:40:40,166 --> 00:40:43,347
a bajillion other factors involved,

725
00:40:43,347 --> 00:40:45,367
we actually saw a 10% increase in retention

726
00:40:45,367 --> 00:40:48,328
in campaign completion rates,

727
00:40:48,328 --> 00:40:52,690
and a 14% increase in co-op completion rates across titles.

728
00:40:55,550 --> 00:40:58,531
And this type of tactic is actually a lot more common

729
00:40:58,531 --> 00:40:59,091
than you think.

730
00:40:59,091 --> 00:41:01,572
It's actually referred to as developing the color script

731
00:41:01,572 --> 00:41:02,912
for your story.

732
00:41:02,912 --> 00:41:05,533
We were heavily influenced by the color script

733
00:41:05,533 --> 00:41:08,454
for Pixar's Up during the development of Gears,

734
00:41:08,454 --> 00:41:11,034
which follows a similar type of progression.

735
00:41:11,034 --> 00:41:13,755
It's completely desaturated in the intro,

736
00:41:13,755 --> 00:41:14,616
cooler in the middle,

737
00:41:14,616 --> 00:41:17,877
and then warm and hyper saturated near the end.

738
00:41:20,592 --> 00:41:30,856
Schindler's List shows how color can serve as a way to really focus someone's attention,

739
00:41:30,856 --> 00:41:35,297
but more importantly, recall those memories at the height of emotional impact

740
00:41:35,297 --> 00:41:36,157
to ensure that they stick around.

741
00:41:36,157 --> 00:41:42,179
Our struggles with game tone in the Gears franchise heavily influenced the development

742
00:41:42,179 --> 00:41:48,041
of our later games. We really asked ourselves what changes we could make to the game

743
00:41:48,041 --> 00:41:49,502
without changing the actual

744
00:41:50,231 --> 00:41:56,253
Gameplay that would hold on to people, more people, for longer periods of time.

745
00:41:56,253 --> 00:42:01,595
And when we were at that point in our discussions, this was Fortnite.

746
00:42:01,595 --> 00:42:05,236
It was very gritty and very violent, just like Gears.

747
00:42:05,236 --> 00:42:10,738
This is Fortnite now. It's whimsical, it's lighthearted, they look completely different.

748
00:42:10,738 --> 00:42:15,080
But the gameplay and the core loop hasn't actually changed.

749
00:42:16,340 --> 00:42:28,209
So if you were going to play Fortnite and retain for days, hours, weeks, months, even years,

750
00:42:28,209 --> 00:42:32,232
which of those two worlds would you want to spend a thousand hours in?

751
00:42:32,232 --> 00:42:35,254
At the time, this barren landscape was Paragon.

752
00:42:35,254 --> 00:42:42,580
This lush environment is Paragon now. Again, where would you want to spend a thousand hours?

753
00:42:43,668 --> 00:42:46,490
It's not to say that you can't make a compelling experience

754
00:42:46,490 --> 00:42:47,530
that's dark or moody.

755
00:42:47,530 --> 00:42:51,133
What I'm trying to say is that with a directed effort,

756
00:42:51,133 --> 00:42:54,855
you can use all of those various feedback channels

757
00:42:54,855 --> 00:42:55,896
to influence retention.

758
00:42:55,896 --> 00:42:59,478
And for us, the intent was to pair

759
00:42:59,478 --> 00:43:01,620
the tactile feedback of the game

760
00:43:01,620 --> 00:43:05,242
with the more visceral feedback of tone and mood

761
00:43:05,242 --> 00:43:07,223
so that we could create an experience

762
00:43:07,223 --> 00:43:10,185
that you look forward to returning to

763
00:43:10,185 --> 00:43:12,087
day after day after day.

764
00:43:16,270 --> 00:43:19,052
So good feedback that helps player understand their feeling

765
00:43:19,052 --> 00:43:23,476
or understand their surroundings at a physical, sensory,

766
00:43:23,476 --> 00:43:26,258
and emotional level can make them feel comfortable,

767
00:43:26,258 --> 00:43:29,200
and powerful, and successful,

768
00:43:29,200 --> 00:43:32,262
leading to the perception that your game is better,

769
00:43:32,262 --> 00:43:35,084
and therefore fostering repeat play.

770
00:43:38,215 --> 00:43:41,518
All right, last category for the day is mental models.

771
00:43:41,518 --> 00:43:43,820
If you understand your player's frame of reference,

772
00:43:43,820 --> 00:43:46,482
you can use it to enhance your design

773
00:43:46,482 --> 00:43:48,003
rather than fight against it

774
00:43:48,003 --> 00:43:50,925
and risk player confusion or even abandonment.

775
00:43:52,352 --> 00:43:55,733
In Fortnite, there are dozens of different objects that you can collect.

776
00:43:55,733 --> 00:43:58,494
Some are meant to be weapons used in combat.

777
00:43:58,494 --> 00:44:02,055
Others are meant as tools that are used for scavenging.

778
00:44:02,055 --> 00:44:04,176
And on paper, this makes perfect sense.

779
00:44:04,176 --> 00:44:07,717
Someone with a broom is unlikely to use it to try and chop down a tree.

780
00:44:07,717 --> 00:44:10,718
Someone with a samurai sword is unlikely to use it to smash rocks.

781
00:44:10,718 --> 00:44:12,039
These are all very rational concepts, right?

782
00:44:16,666 --> 00:44:20,870
But our UX testing actually proved the unreliability

783
00:44:20,870 --> 00:44:22,992
of those rational design decisions.

784
00:44:22,992 --> 00:44:25,894
This is a player from one of our UX tests

785
00:44:25,894 --> 00:44:29,197
who tried for several minutes

786
00:44:29,197 --> 00:44:31,379
to smash rocks with a sledgehammer.

787
00:44:31,379 --> 00:44:33,661
But in the world of Fortnite,

788
00:44:33,661 --> 00:44:35,563
hammers are weapons, not tools.

789
00:44:35,563 --> 00:44:37,445
So they don't work for harvesting.

790
00:44:38,582 --> 00:44:44,044
In another test, players were totally confused when a stick was actually three times faster

791
00:44:44,044 --> 00:44:46,986
at chopping down a tree than an axe was.

792
00:44:46,986 --> 00:44:50,227
The axe is a dedicated weapon, not a tool.

793
00:44:50,227 --> 00:44:56,710
The design intent didn't match with the player's mental model of how these objects should function.

794
00:44:56,710 --> 00:44:59,111
This caused frustration.

795
00:44:59,111 --> 00:45:04,353
It made the game feel very much like a long grind, which pushed players away.

796
00:45:05,499 --> 00:45:12,144
Eventually, we separated the weapon and harvesting systems so that each progresses and operates

797
00:45:12,144 --> 00:45:12,565
independently.

798
00:45:12,565 --> 00:45:18,469
And after that change, we saw significantly less confusion about harvesting in our UX

799
00:45:18,469 --> 00:45:18,810
tests.

800
00:45:18,810 --> 00:45:24,434
And, again, while there's a million other things that went into the two builds, we actually

801
00:45:24,434 --> 00:45:29,038
saw a 10% increase in repeat play amongst new players.

802
00:45:32,688 --> 00:45:35,730
Conventions like using an ax to chop wood

803
00:45:35,730 --> 00:45:38,811
can be important in other ways as well.

804
00:45:38,811 --> 00:45:42,373
Diablo has a red globe of liquid health on the left

805
00:45:42,373 --> 00:45:45,335
and a blue globe of liquid mana on the right.

806
00:45:45,335 --> 00:45:48,017
So when you find a red potion in game,

807
00:45:48,017 --> 00:45:50,578
there's a pretty strong affordance for what it'll do.

808
00:45:50,578 --> 00:45:53,700
It matches player expectations, making it easy to learn.

809
00:45:53,700 --> 00:45:54,160
But that's not Diablo.

810
00:45:54,160 --> 00:45:56,622
That's actually Path of Exile.

811
00:45:56,622 --> 00:45:58,102
And here is Arbiter's Judgment.

812
00:46:01,811 --> 00:46:04,894
And here is torchlight, I could go on.

813
00:46:04,894 --> 00:46:09,718
Similar games, similar genres, similar gameplay, similar UI.

814
00:46:09,718 --> 00:46:11,720
Why reinvent the wheel?

815
00:46:11,720 --> 00:46:17,065
People use known conventions as a means to learn new things.

816
00:46:17,065 --> 00:46:19,107
So you can make their experience better

817
00:46:19,107 --> 00:46:20,288
by taking advantage of that.

818
00:46:20,288 --> 00:46:24,012
The less that players have to struggle to learn new things,

819
00:46:24,012 --> 00:46:26,414
the more likely they are to stick around.

820
00:46:27,556 --> 00:46:32,140
This means that affordances are actually pretty fantastic for retention.

821
00:46:32,140 --> 00:46:35,523
You see a piata, you want to hit the piata.

822
00:46:35,523 --> 00:46:36,604
How do you hit it?

823
00:46:36,604 --> 00:46:38,386
You swing back your weapon.

824
00:46:38,386 --> 00:46:42,730
And sometimes when you hit them, the piata switches from paper to silver,

825
00:46:42,730 --> 00:46:45,733
or from silver to diamond-studded gold.

826
00:46:45,733 --> 00:46:49,657
And you get a pretty good sense that it's actually been upgraded

827
00:46:49,657 --> 00:46:52,239
and that the items inside will be more valuable.

828
00:46:53,273 --> 00:46:56,475
We never taught players this because what's intuitive

829
00:46:56,475 --> 00:46:57,615
doesn't need to be learned.

830
00:46:57,615 --> 00:46:59,856
It hits us at that visceral level

831
00:46:59,856 --> 00:47:02,137
and positively affects our behavior.

832
00:47:02,137 --> 00:47:05,298
So gameplay is more natural and with fewer hurdles,

833
00:47:05,298 --> 00:47:07,098
people are more likely to stick around,

834
00:47:07,098 --> 00:47:10,179
to think about the game more, to be reflective

835
00:47:10,179 --> 00:47:12,140
and to come back and play more.

836
00:47:12,140 --> 00:47:15,121
And I know that sounds like a totally obvious,

837
00:47:15,121 --> 00:47:17,222
pointless statement to make,

838
00:47:17,222 --> 00:47:20,183
but when you're caught up in the complexities of development

839
00:47:20,654 --> 00:47:24,357
with interacting goals and personalities and deadlines.

840
00:47:24,357 --> 00:47:27,780
These sort of things really often tend to slip through.

841
00:47:27,780 --> 00:47:29,541
Take the tower design in Paragon.

842
00:47:29,541 --> 00:47:32,243
This giant thing right here is a tower.

843
00:47:32,243 --> 00:47:33,844
It's several stories tall,

844
00:47:33,844 --> 00:47:36,947
arguably the most important thing in the game,

845
00:47:36,947 --> 00:47:38,048
pretty hard to miss.

846
00:47:38,048 --> 00:47:40,910
It's right there in the middle of the screen.

847
00:47:40,910 --> 00:47:43,232
It's the focal point for all team play.

848
00:47:43,232 --> 00:47:46,054
You destroy towers to advance and win the game.

849
00:47:46,695 --> 00:47:49,617
So we put tons of resources into their design.

850
00:47:49,617 --> 00:47:52,018
And yet, in our original implementation,

851
00:47:52,018 --> 00:47:54,419
we totally over-rationalized.

852
00:47:54,419 --> 00:47:57,420
When you're in a game, the actual physical tower

853
00:47:57,420 --> 00:47:58,561
is completely off screen.

854
00:47:58,561 --> 00:48:03,203
And what you attack is the gem that powers it.

855
00:48:03,203 --> 00:48:05,184
The gem doesn't look dangerous or protected.

856
00:48:05,184 --> 00:48:07,965
It's completely amorphous.

857
00:48:07,965 --> 00:48:10,847
And when it does attack, the tower hits you

858
00:48:10,847 --> 00:48:13,488
from somewhere completely disconnected from your view.

859
00:48:14,168 --> 00:48:16,109
So it's difficult to make that association

860
00:48:16,109 --> 00:48:17,809
between cause and effect.

861
00:48:17,809 --> 00:48:20,550
And in our UX test, we saw people tower diving

862
00:48:20,550 --> 00:48:23,291
over and over and dying over and over.

863
00:48:23,291 --> 00:48:25,652
Rather than attack the gem,

864
00:48:25,652 --> 00:48:27,993
some of them even turn to attack the actual tower

865
00:48:27,993 --> 00:48:31,014
that was shooting them, which makes perfect sense,

866
00:48:31,014 --> 00:48:34,155
but that has no gameplay effect whatsoever.

867
00:48:34,155 --> 00:48:35,715
All it does is get you killed.

868
00:48:36,734 --> 00:48:39,437
This poor participant from one of our UX tests

869
00:48:39,437 --> 00:48:41,279
played on easy mode versus AI,

870
00:48:41,279 --> 00:48:44,962
which is, in theory, nearly impossible to lose.

871
00:48:44,962 --> 00:48:48,686
And after a brutal hour and a half match,

872
00:48:48,686 --> 00:48:52,931
lost the game and came away with zero kills, 35 deaths,

873
00:48:52,931 --> 00:48:55,713
almost every single one of them

874
00:48:55,713 --> 00:48:58,116
due to repeatedly running under a tower and dying.

875
00:48:59,465 --> 00:49:01,645
And we saw this type of behavior very regularly

876
00:49:01,645 --> 00:49:02,345
with new players.

877
00:49:02,345 --> 00:49:04,406
It was a critical issue in our UX reports

878
00:49:04,406 --> 00:49:06,646
because it was frustrating

879
00:49:06,646 --> 00:49:09,287
and it pushed players away from the game.

880
00:49:09,287 --> 00:49:09,867
So we changed tower designs.

881
00:49:09,867 --> 00:49:14,048
Now the gems actually look more like towers.

882
00:49:14,048 --> 00:49:17,148
They have shields over them to protect them

883
00:49:17,148 --> 00:49:20,049
and the shields fall when they're vulnerable.

884
00:49:20,049 --> 00:49:21,970
And when that tower attacks you,

885
00:49:21,970 --> 00:49:25,670
the beam comes straight from the thing that you're attacking

886
00:49:25,670 --> 00:49:28,091
so you can better associate cause and effect.

887
00:49:28,731 --> 00:49:32,915
and they now have rings around the outside that are red when it's dangerous to approach

888
00:49:32,915 --> 00:49:37,299
and green when it's safe. Sorry if you're colorblind, still a work in progress.

889
00:49:37,299 --> 00:49:44,145
But as of our most recent UX tests, tower deaths have actually significantly decreased

890
00:49:44,145 --> 00:49:49,129
and players seem to understand towers much better and are less frustrated overall.

891
00:49:50,360 --> 00:49:56,061
This goes to show that affordances run deeper than just looking at an object in the world.

892
00:49:56,061 --> 00:49:58,062
They apply to game systems as well.

893
00:49:58,062 --> 00:50:05,103
So if you can design situations and systems so that it's easy and intuitive to do the

894
00:50:05,103 --> 00:50:11,705
right thing and hard to do the wrong thing, people will find success, feel empowered,

895
00:50:11,705 --> 00:50:13,085
and stay in your game.

896
00:50:15,536 --> 00:50:19,997
Now, of course, these are only a few of the factors that could enhance retention in games,

897
00:50:19,997 --> 00:50:25,559
and when I was putting together this talk, I couldn't decide whether I wanted to talk

898
00:50:25,559 --> 00:50:31,000
about the way that emotion affects design, or the way that design affects emotion.

899
00:50:31,000 --> 00:50:37,482
And in the end, I really couldn't easily separate the two, and that's one of the reasons that

900
00:50:37,482 --> 00:50:39,523
I think emotional design is so important.

901
00:50:40,238 --> 00:50:41,819
It's universal.

902
00:50:41,819 --> 00:50:45,441
So if you can address the visceral, behavioral,

903
00:50:45,441 --> 00:50:47,923
and reflective components all in one design,

904
00:50:47,923 --> 00:50:50,264
you're more likely to hit on something

905
00:50:50,264 --> 00:50:54,046
that is applicable to a broad audience of humans

906
00:50:54,046 --> 00:50:59,230
rather than satisfy one small group or niche audience.

907
00:50:59,230 --> 00:51:01,071
That's all I have for today.

908
00:51:01,071 --> 00:51:05,073
Thank you very much for your time.

909
00:51:05,073 --> 00:51:05,393
Thank you.

910
00:51:11,946 --> 00:51:14,487
I think we still have about five minutes or so. Yes.

911
00:51:14,487 --> 00:51:17,929
For questions and please do fill out surveys.

912
00:51:17,929 --> 00:51:21,551
We'd love to hear what you thought. Tell me how I screwed it up or how I was

913
00:51:21,551 --> 00:51:22,852
wrong. Yeah, go ahead.

914
00:51:23,381 --> 00:51:27,203
Hi Jim, this is Ryan Miller from Deep Silver Volition.

915
00:51:27,203 --> 00:51:29,484
When you were discussing the social aspect,

916
00:51:29,484 --> 00:51:32,205
you were referring primarily to the multiplayer aspect.

917
00:51:32,205 --> 00:51:34,986
I do remember that Gears of War, you had squads with you.

918
00:51:34,986 --> 00:51:37,327
And I know that players respond relatively well

919
00:51:37,327 --> 00:51:41,209
to the mentor effect of seeing an AI ally do something.

920
00:51:41,209 --> 00:51:43,750
Did that have any effect, do you think, on retention?

921
00:51:44,329 --> 00:51:53,474
Yeah absolutely, as I mentioned it's not just guilds or clans or whatever, just being on a team has that same kind of impact.

922
00:51:53,474 --> 00:51:59,137
And in Gears we actually specifically designed Dom to be more like your conscious.

923
00:51:59,137 --> 00:52:05,060
So he would say the obvious things that we wanted players to notice but they didn't necessarily.

924
00:52:05,060 --> 00:52:08,281
And that helped players understand kind of puzzles and situations.

925
00:52:08,802 --> 00:52:14,889
And then each of the characters in your squad had kind of a specific personality that would offset different things

926
00:52:14,889 --> 00:52:19,674
that would really basically existed to help you understand the game or

927
00:52:19,674 --> 00:52:25,761
get more into the story or more attached to them as people. Each of them had a very specific role that we were hoping they

928
00:52:25,761 --> 00:52:26,803
would fill out.

929
00:52:26,803 --> 00:52:28,104
Okay, thank you for that information.

930
00:52:30,574 --> 00:52:35,737
Hi, I'm Hannah Murphy. I'm a new user researcher. I do freelance game user research.

931
00:52:35,737 --> 00:52:35,897
Uh-huh.

932
00:52:35,897 --> 00:52:42,161
Um, as you're talking about character design and becoming more realistic, um,

933
00:52:42,161 --> 00:52:47,204
what are your thoughts on Uncanny Valley and do you see that being an issue?

934
00:52:47,204 --> 00:52:53,488
It's, it is. It's a huge issue, right? And it's something you have to be very, very careful with.

935
00:52:53,488 --> 00:52:55,349
Uh, generally speaking, it's a lot easier.

936
00:52:56,057 --> 00:53:03,661
cheaper, faster, all of those good things to embrace kind of the cartoony side of things because

937
00:53:03,661 --> 00:53:07,182
if you don't make it all the way across the uncanny valley you're going to fall into it

938
00:53:07,182 --> 00:53:13,505
and so you have to be very very careful with that kind of stuff. As time has gone on we have

939
00:53:13,505 --> 00:53:18,827
actually realized the high production cost of these kind of characters and just recently have

940
00:53:18,827 --> 00:53:20,848
kind of started to pull back from that a little bit more.

941
00:53:21,489 --> 00:53:25,773
So you'll probably start seeing the effects of that later as we get into game,

942
00:53:25,773 --> 00:53:28,335
but I was just talking to one of our animators this week who is,

943
00:53:28,335 --> 00:53:31,798
their entire design philosophy has shifted because of that.

944
00:53:31,798 --> 00:53:33,860
Just knowing how much effort is involved,

945
00:53:33,860 --> 00:53:38,024
and there's no guarantee that you're always going to make it across that uncanny valley,

946
00:53:38,024 --> 00:53:39,545
so it can be very dangerous to even try.

947
00:53:39,545 --> 00:53:39,926
Thanks.

948
00:53:43,927 --> 00:53:45,267
Hi Jim, Gina Smith from 2K.

949
00:53:45,267 --> 00:53:49,968
So I really appreciate that you used a lot of different games

950
00:53:49,968 --> 00:53:52,148
as examples throughout this from different platforms

951
00:53:52,148 --> 00:53:53,909
and different genres.

952
00:53:53,909 --> 00:53:56,209
And I guess my question is, have you found that

953
00:53:56,209 --> 00:53:59,290
the platform on which a game stands

954
00:53:59,290 --> 00:54:00,710
or even the genre that it comes from

955
00:54:00,710 --> 00:54:02,350
affects these design principles at all?

956
00:54:02,350 --> 00:54:06,631
It definitely can, but I would say it's more about

957
00:54:06,631 --> 00:54:08,771
how well you reach your target audience.

958
00:54:08,771 --> 00:54:10,792
You know, it doesn't matter if you're making

959
00:54:10,792 --> 00:54:12,672
a platformer versus a shooter.

960
00:54:13,559 --> 00:54:16,662
What matters is if you're making a platform for shooter people, right?

961
00:54:16,662 --> 00:54:19,344
That's going to affect it more than just, I think, the general platform.

962
00:54:19,344 --> 00:54:20,786
Absolutely.

963
00:54:20,786 --> 00:54:23,168
And access to whatever platform that is.

964
00:54:23,168 --> 00:54:26,351
Mobile maybe, higher, because there's more of them.

965
00:54:26,351 --> 00:54:26,751
Thank you.

966
00:54:29,827 --> 00:54:31,287
Hi Jim, thanks for your talk.

967
00:54:31,287 --> 00:54:34,089
Nikki Crenshaw, I'm a PhD candidate at UC Irvine.

968
00:54:34,089 --> 00:54:35,870
So you were talking about kind of like,

969
00:54:35,870 --> 00:54:37,991
if it looks like Diablo, we expect it to play like Diablo,

970
00:54:37,991 --> 00:54:40,552
that kind of like establishing player patterns and stuff

971
00:54:40,552 --> 00:54:41,493
from the way a game looks.

972
00:54:41,493 --> 00:54:44,494
And this is something I've been thinking about for a while

973
00:54:44,494 --> 00:54:46,816
where like, does this limit kind of what devs are able to do

974
00:54:46,816 --> 00:54:48,497
in terms of creativity?

975
00:54:48,497 --> 00:54:50,017
James Berg, I don't know if he's in here still,

976
00:54:50,017 --> 00:54:51,478
but he gave a talk a few years ago

977
00:54:51,478 --> 00:54:52,759
about they were doing some testing

978
00:54:52,759 --> 00:54:54,180
and it was a character that had a spear,

979
00:54:54,180 --> 00:54:56,581
but shot fireballs and all of these players were dying.

980
00:54:56,641 --> 00:55:00,163
they weren't expecting it to have magic abilities if it was holding a spear.

981
00:55:00,163 --> 00:55:05,487
So is there a way for us to get out of kind of like, like breaking player expectations

982
00:55:05,487 --> 00:55:09,710
in a way that helps them learn or helps them break out of patterns that we've already like

983
00:55:09,710 --> 00:55:10,070
really deep.

984
00:55:10,454 --> 00:55:15,236
established. I think so it's not about I think limiting our creativity in terms

985
00:55:15,236 --> 00:55:19,198
of like oh if I'm making a Diablo like game it should look like Diablo it's

986
00:55:19,198 --> 00:55:23,980
more about finding those particular aspects of your game that you don't need

987
00:55:23,980 --> 00:55:28,562
to reinvent the wheel on so that you can focus on those new elements that

988
00:55:28,562 --> 00:55:32,404
actually enhance learning and creativity and you don't spend your dev cycles

989
00:55:32,404 --> 00:55:35,845
working on the things that you don't need to worry about so you can make them

990
00:55:36,425 --> 00:55:39,647
easier by making them intuitive or by using their own conventions,

991
00:55:39,647 --> 00:55:41,167
matching mental models, all those things.

992
00:55:41,167 --> 00:55:43,768
So that the player gets those things intuitively,

993
00:55:43,768 --> 00:55:47,930
and then your dev effort can go into the more creative and new elements

994
00:55:47,930 --> 00:55:51,231
that are unique to your game, whatever that is,

995
00:55:51,231 --> 00:55:54,913
and really, you know, shining the spotlight on those,

996
00:55:54,913 --> 00:55:56,554
because that's what's going to make your game stand out.

997
00:55:56,554 --> 00:55:56,814
Cool. Thank you.

998
00:56:00,337 --> 00:56:02,280
